    {
      "id": "6ac679aafe4e91c4c8e6ca7aee0c8f1ac7c07070",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2020-12-06 03:36:32.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1\n\n(1 comment)\n\nI think the \"real\" answer is that the library version shouldn't change its major number if there is no incompatible change to the API/ABI.  That is something that I have been trying to avoid, so it isn't clear if there is a reason to change the major library version.  I think it would be reasonable to use 1:$LUSTRE_MAJOR:$LUSTRE_MINOR for this?\n\nA better check would be to have some verification of the llapi functions (maybe part of checkpatch.pl?) to verify that the function signatures are not changing, and add a warning if there are new llapi functions added to lustreapi.h that are not being verified (which would be a good reason to bump the minor number).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
